$$I(t)=V(D;S;t)$$

Data $D$ is transformed according to a specification $S$ into a time varying image $I(t)$.

The image $I$ is perceived by a user, with an increase in knowledge $K$ as a result:

$$\frac{dK}{dt} = P(I;K).$$

($P$ = Cognition; $E$ = Exploration).

"In other words, a great visualization method is used by many people, who use it routinely to obtain highly valuable knowledge, without having to spend time and money on hardware, software, and effort. Indeed, quite obvious."

Motion graphics

  • Moving beautiful infographics.

Comics

  • Scott McCloudâ€™s theory on representation vs abstraction from Understanding Comics

Animation

  • Drawing on representational style of comics, but using persistence of vision and change over time to make drawing appear to move. Also 3D graphics.

Video games

  • As an extension of comics and animation, but including interactivity. The evolution over time, from very crude (pong), through more realistic (I was blown away by Wolfenstein 3D), to todayâ€™s games with breathtaking beauty.

User interface (UI) design

  • In parallel to video game development, but with a different utility and hence different focus.

See also, User experience (UX) design

Web design

  • A merging of user interface design and graphic design, that has become so widespread it is worthy of separate consideration.
